Groupon, Inc. Key Developments

Groupon, Inc. Announces Unaudited Consolidated Earnings Results for the Second Quarter and Six Months Ended June 30, 2017; Updates Earnings Outlook for 2017
Aug 2 17
Groupon, Inc. announced unaudited consolidated earnings results for the second quarter and six months ended June 30, 2017. For the quarter, the company reported total revenue was $662,619,000 against $723,760,000 a year ago. Loss from operations was $7,398,000 against $39,753,000 a year ago. Loss from continuing operations before provision was $1,520,000 against $51,006,000 a year ago. Loss from continuing operations was $5,403,000 against $48,768,000 a year ago. Net loss attributable to company was $9,326,000 against $54,904,000 a year ago. Basic and diluted net loss per share from continuing operations was $0.01 against $0.09 a year ago. Basic and diluted net loss per share was $0.02 against $0.1 a year ago. Net cash used in operating activities was $21,792,000 against $54,010,000 a year ago. Purchases of property and equipment and capitalized software were $15,385,000 against $16,499,000 a year ago. Acquisitions of intangible assets and other investing activities was $240,000 against $1,206,000 a year ago. Adjusted EBITDA was $53,293,000 compared to $35,586,000 a year ago. Non-GAAP net income attributable to common stockholders was of $11,955,000 or $0.02 per share. 

For the six months, the company reported total revenue was $1,336,245,000 against $1,422,195,000 a year ago. Loss from operations was $19,078,000 against $84,901,000 a year ago. Loss from continuing operations before provision was $17,802,000 against $93,536,000 a year ago. Loss from continuing operations was $26,272,000 against $92,307,000 a year ago. Net loss attributable to company was $33,740,000 against $104,023,000 a year ago. Basic and diluted net loss per share from continuing operations was $0.06 against $0.17 a year ago. Basic and diluted net loss per share was $0.06 against $0.18 a year ago. Net cash used in operating activities was $159,123,000 against $130,735,000 a year ago. Purchases of property and equipment and capitalized software were $29,461,000 against $36,351,000 a year ago. Acquisitions of intangible assets and other investing activities was $184,000 against $1,992,000 a year ago. Non-GAAP net income attributable to common stockholders was of $17,127,000 or $0.03 per share.

The company is updating its outlook for 2017, which reflects current foreign exchange rates, as well as expected marketing investments and cost benefits associated with streamlining initiatives. The basis for full year 2017 guidance is continuing operations. For the full year 2017, the company expects gross profit to be in the range of $1.30 billion to $1.35 billion, which is unchanged. Groupon is raising the bottom end of its expected Adjusted EBITDA guidance range to $215 million to $240 million in 2017.


Groupon and Grubhub Announce Strategic Partnership to Bring Food Delivery to Groupon Customers Throughout the United States
Jul 31 17
Groupon and Grubhub announced a strategic partnership to bring food delivery to Groupon customers throughout the United States. As part of the deal, Groupon and Grubhub have entered into a commercial agreement that will allow Groupon to provide users with the ability to order food delivery from Grubhub’s 55,000 restaurant partners via the Groupon platform and is expected to enable people to redeem Groupon deals when they order Grubhub delivery via Groupon.


Groupon Names Aaron Cooper as President of North America
Jul 20 17
Groupon announced that it has named Aaron Cooper as President of North America, giving him oversight of the company’s Local, Travel and Goods businesses in the United States and Canada. Cooper currently serves as Senior Vice President of North America Services, which includes Local and Travel, and will continue in that capacity while adding responsibility for the Goods North America business. Cooper first joined Groupon in 2010, serving as chief marketing officer, head of North America Travel and head of North America Goods before assuming his current role in December 2015. In his new role, he will continue to play a leadership role in shaping the company’s ongoing card-linked offers and beauty-booking voucherless initiatives designed to create a more convenient and easy experience for both customers and merchants and improve frequency.


